# Styling Conventions

## Approach

- **Vue files**: Use **Tailwind utility classes** for layout, spacing, typography, borders, and colours. Prefer semantic colour classes (see below) over hardcoded values.
- **Colour theming**: Define **all colour tokens in `.css` files** (e.g. `resources/css/app.css`). Use semantic names so the site can be rethemed site-wide and/or per user without touching Vue.
- **Styling in Vue, not JS**: Avoid applying styling in `.js`/`.ts` files (e.g. class strings, inline styles). Prefer creating `.vue` components and reusing them from JS; keep layout and appearance in templates and CSS.

## Semantic colour classes (use these in Vue)

Use Tailwind classes that map to **CSS theme variables** only. Do **not** use built-in Tailwind colour utilities (e.g. `red-500`, `neutral-800`, `blue-600`) for theme colours — use semantic tokens such as `theme-bg`, `theme-text`, `theme-accent-1`, `theme-border`, etc.

Add new colours as CSS variables and `@theme` entries in `app.css`; then use the corresponding Tailwind class in Vue (e.g. `--color-accent-1` → `theme-accent-1` utility).

## Breakpoints and layout

- **Desktop**: viewport ≥ 1280×720. Treat as default for multi-column and richer layouts.
- **Mobile**: viewport &lt; 1280×720. Prefer **stacked, single-column** layout (e.g. `flex flex-col`, single-column grid, stacked sections). Use Tailwind breakpoints (e.g. `max-[1279px]:` or a custom `sm`/`md` that aligns to 1280px) so desktop gets wider layout and mobile gets the stacked layout.

## Rules

- **No** styling in `.js`/`.ts` — use Vue components for UI; reuse them from JS where layout/colours are needed.
- **No** built-in Tailwind colour classes for theme colours; use semantic classes only (e.g. `theme-background`, `theme-text`, not `bg-white`, `text-gray-900`).
- **No** hardcoded colour values in Vue (no `bg-[#fff]`, `text-red-500`). Use semantic classes only.
- **No** inline styles for colours. Use Tailwind classes that reference the theme.
- For user customization: override CSS variables (e.g. in a user-specific class or `<style>` that sets `--accent-1`, `--bg`, etc.) so Vue markup stays unchanged.
- **No dark mode**: Dark variant/support is removed. To change the look, swap themes (e.g. named theme classes that override CSS variables) rather than toggling light/dark.
- **Mobile first for layout**: Prefer single-column/stacked by default; add multi-column or side-by-side layout at desktop breakpoint (1280px).
